This new species is similar to
Bignonia potosina
(K.Schum. & Loes.) L.G.Lohmann, but is distinguished by its membranous leaflets with mixed opposite-alternate percurrent tertiary venation (vs. chartaceous with alternate percurrent tertiary venation in
Bignonia potosina
), membranous calyx (vs. chartaceous calyx in
Bignonia potosina
) and fruits shorter than 6.8 cm long (vs. fruits longer than 15 cm in
Bignonia potosina
). Table 2 .

This species is found in evergreen or semideciduous forests in Western Amazonia, occurring in Bolivia (Beni, La Paz and Santa Cruz) and Brazil (Acre, Amazonas and Mato Grosso), between 160 to 700 m alt. (Fig. 
4
).
